public final class Key
extends Scale

A Key is just what we think it is, and is sort of where we tie together all the harmonic things defined at lower levels. We must always assume a Key is a major or minor scale represented with 0-7 flats or sharps, which occur in circle-of-fifths order. That is what most of the logic below accomplishes. This provides us with 30 total keys to write in.

Author:
Jon

getNoteName

public java.lang.String getNoteName(int i)
Gets the note name for the given note using this Key's root name. Assumes this is a heptatonic key (i.e., major, minor or modal) that can be represented with only sharps, flats, double sharps and double flats. Naturals will also be represented if the key assumes a note is flat. Depending on this key, results will change accidentals dynamically. For instance: Key | A | Ab C | A | Ab C- | An| A

Parameters:
i -
Returns:
